# [src/screens/BiometricLockScreen.tsx](file:///c:/Users/HP/Downloads/expensetracker/mobile/src/screens/BiometricLockScreen.tsx) - Technical Explanation

This file acts as a mandatory security gatehouse. If the user turns on the "App Lock" setting, this screen appears instantly whenever the app opens, blocking all access until a physical fingerprint or FaceID scan occurs.

## 1. Native API & Hardware Bindings (Lines 14-60)
```tsx
import ReactNativeBiometrics, { BiometryTypes } from 'react-native-biometrics';

const checkBiometrics = async () => {
    const { available, biometryType } = await rnBiometrics.isSensorAvailable();

    if (available) {
        setBiometryType(biometryType || 'Biometrics');
        setTimeout(() => authenticate(), 300); // Auto-prompt on load
    } else {
        // ... No biometrics - allow entry (fallback)
    }
};
```
*   **Syntax**: `ReactNativeBiometrics` reaches underneath the Javascript layer directly into the iOS Secure Enclave or the Android Keystore system.
*   **Logical Flow**: The moment the screen physically loads onto the display (`useEffect`), it queries the phone's hardware. If it detects a face scanner or fingerprint reader, it forces an immediate 300ms auto-prompt to scan the user without making them tap any buttons manually.

## 2. Hardware Authentication Flow (Lines 62-92)
```tsx
    const authenticate = async () => {
        setIsAuthenticating(true);
        try {
            const { success } = await rnBiometrics.simplePrompt({
                promptMessage: 'Unlock Expense Tracker',
            });

            if (success) {
                await AsyncStorage.setItem(LAST_UNLOCK_KEY, Date.now().toString());
                onUnlock();
            }
        } catch (error: any) {
            if (error?.message?.includes('cancelled')) return;
        }
    };
```
*   **Logical Flow**: 
    1. Triggers the OS-level biometric popup ("Unlock Expense Tracker").
    2. If the scanner passes the biological check, it writes a timestamp to the device hard drive so the app remembers *when* it was unlocked.
    3. It fires the `onUnlock()` callback function. This function was passed down from the master Root Navigation file ([App.tsx](file:///c:/Users/HP/Downloads/expensetracker/mobile/App.tsx)), which physically deletes this Lock overlay and reveals the Dashboard underneath it.

## 3. UI and OS-Level Handlers (Lines 36-39 & 94-114)
```tsx
    useEffect(() => {
        // Prevent back button from closing app
        const backHandler = BackHandler.addEventListener('hardwareBackPress', () => true);
        return () => backHandler.remove();
    }, []);
```
*   **Logical Flow (Security Layer)**: On Android devices, users have a physical "Back" triangle button on their navigation bar. It intercepts that button press and returns `true` (meaning "I handled this event"). This intercepts the system and prevents the user from pressing "Back" to bypass the lock screen.
